Hi Mike, Mike and Glenn.&lt;br&gt;
This is my humb=
le take:&lt;br&gt;
1. Application is far more that just a component. My definitio=
n includes business goals and the like, so I won&#39;t enter there.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br=
&gt;
2. A system includes not only the components but the inter-relationships,=
 interfaces and externally visible properties. As I once stated in this for=
um, a client is a role, and can be played by one component inside a system =
A, and by another system B consuming services on System A. So we can have a=
 system of systems, where their components can be playing different roles, =
one of them being a client.&lt;br&gt;


&lt;br&gt;
3. That clarified, REST is an archit=
ectural style that defines component roles and rules of engagement to achie=
ve a set of quality properties. Theory says that one component not playing =
the role or not following the rules, may affect the property quality achiev=
ement. Clear?&lt;br&gt;


&lt;br&gt;
4. Now, in any modern architecture development, we=
 architects should not focus only in functional requirements, but in qualit=
y properties too. That means making decisions about how things are going to=
 work, stating policies and making sure those policies are enforced. Follow=
ing this line of thinking, implementing an architectural conception that fo=
llows REST style, but that does not enforce the rules or does not even dete=
ct a rule is being broken (a governance problem), I should say it is a weak=
 implementation. And if we are not in control of all components (other peop=
le creating their services and clients) then we may not achieve the quality=
 properties after all.&lt;br&gt;


&lt;br&gt;
5. But all that is not REST fault, and sh=
ouldn&#39;t care less. That is the work of the architect, designers and dev=
elopers and other stakeholders. REST is not an out-of-the-box solution you =
get when you install a framework and use it. A framework may help, but the =
actual success of delivering business value comes from the work of all peop=
le. You will get nowhere if a bunch of your developers keep not following t=
he rules. If an external &quot;client&quot; enters the system, and is not p=
laying the rules, may affect the quality properties, and sure it will suffe=
r itself from that, when the server changes the uri namespace or the flow, =
then it becomes a problem of the spoiled client. &lt;br&gt;


&lt;br&gt;
My two cents.&lt;=
br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
William Martinez Pomares&lt;br&gt;
